{
  format: 1
  name: composite-int-component-tiebreak-in-sorted-view
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.5", "§B.4", "§B.1", "§7.3"]
  tags: ["ordering"]
  note: '''
    §B.5 tiebreak (after a tied declared $sort): the row identity, ordered by
    the $key VALUE order. §B.4 composite key: "lexicographic components in $key
    order", each component in its own type order (§B.1). Here $key is
    [region, seq] with seq an int. Attack: a runtime whose declared-$sort
    tiebreak orders the composite identity by its joined canonical TEXT
    ("eu:10" / "eu:2" / "eu:3" -> 10, 2, 3) instead of component-wise value
    order. Within region "eu" the value order is 2 < 3 < 10.

    Every row ties on grp = "x", so the declared key is equal and the order is
    fixed entirely by the composite identity: eu/2, eu/3, eu/10. Asserted on the
    distinct text `tag` fields (two, three, ten), the REVERSE of the text-join
    misreading. Seed member names use the ':'-joined canonical key text (D.2).
    The companion default-order case (composite-key-second-component-uses-int-order)
    covers the UNsorted path; this one covers the sorted-view tiebreak.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.tiecomp@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      slots: {
        $key: ["region", "seq"]
        region: "text"
        seq: "int"
        grp: "text"
        tag: "text"
      }
      $public: {
        bygrp: { $view: ".slots { tag, grp, $sort: [grp] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      slots: {
        "eu:2":  { grp: "x", tag: "two" }
        "eu:10": { grp: "x", tag: "ten" }
        "eu:3":  { grp: "x", tag: "three" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.bygrp", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { tag: "two",   grp: "x" }
        { tag: "three", grp: "x" }
        { tag: "ten",   grp: "x" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
